# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: applejack-drink
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Born in a one-room log cabin in Kentucky, Lincoln was raised on the frontier.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] He was self-educated and became a lawyer, Illinois state legislator, and U.S. representative.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Angered by the Kansas–Nebraska Act of 1854, which opened the territories to slavery, he became a leader of the new Republican Party.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] He reached a national audience in the 1858 Senate campaign debates against Stephen A.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln won the 1860 presidential election, becoming the first Republican president.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] His victory prompted a majority of the slave states to begin seceding and form the Confederate States.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] A month after Lincoln assumed the presidency, Confederate forces attacked Fort Sumter, starting the Civil War.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] As a moderate Republican, Lincoln had to navigate conflicting political opinions from contentious factions during the war effort.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] He closely supervised the Union's strategy and tactics, including the selection of generals and the implementation of a naval blockade of Southern ports.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] He suspended the writ of *habeas corpus* in April 1861, an action that Chief Justice Roger Taney found in *Ex parte Merryman* that only Congress could do, and he averted war with Britain by defusing the *Trent* Affair.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 1, 1863, he issued the Emancipation Proclamation, which declared the slaves in the states "in rebellion" to be free.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] On November 19, 1863, he delivered the Gettysburg Address, which became one of the most famous speeches in American history.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] He promoted the Thirteenth Amendment to the U.S.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Constitution, which, in 1865, abolished chattel slavery.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Following his re-election in 1864, he sought to heal the war-torn nation through Reconstruction.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] On April 14, 1865, five days after the Confederate surrender at Appomattox, Lincoln was fatally shot by John Wilkes Booth at Ford's Theatre in Washington, D.C., becoming the first U.S. president to be assassinated.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln is remembered as a martyr and a national hero for his wartime leadership and for his efforts to preserve the Union and abolish slavery.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] He is consistently ranked in both popular and scholarly polls as among the greatest presidents in American history.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Born in a one-room log cabin in Kentucky on February 12, 1809, Abraham Lincoln was raised on Sinking Spring Farm near Hodgenville, Kentucky.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] The captain was killed in a Native American raid in 1786.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] The family settled in Hardin County, Kentucky, in the early 1800s.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nancy is widely assumed to have been the daughter of Lucy Hanks.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas and Nancy married on June 12, 1806, and moved to Elizabethtown, Kentucky.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] They had three children: Sarah, Abraham, and Thomas Jr., who died as an infant.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's father bought multiple farms in Kentucky but could not get clear property titles to any, losing hundreds of acres in legal disputes.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1816, the family moved to Indiana, where land titles were more reliable.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] They settled on a forested plot in Little Pigeon Creek Community.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] In Kentucky and Indiana, Thomas worked as a farmer, cabinetmaker, and carpenter.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] At various times, he owned farms, livestock, and town lots, appraised estates, and served on county patrols.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas and Nancy were members of a Separate Baptist Church, a pious evangelical group whose members largely opposed slavery.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Overcoming financial challenges, Thomas obtained clear title to 80 acres (32 ha) in Little Pigeon Creek Community in 1827.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] On October 5, 1818, Nancy died from milk sickness, leaving 11-year-old Sarah in charge of the household, which included her father, 9-year-old Abraham, and Nancy's 19-year-old orphan cousin, Dennis Hanks.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas married Sarah Bush Johnston, a widow with three children of her own, on December 2, 1819.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Abraham became close to his stepmother and called her "Mama".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 20, 1828, Lincoln's sister died in childbirth, devastating him.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] His formal schooling was from itinerant teachers.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] It included two short stints in Kentucky, where he learned to read, but probably not to write.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] After moving to Indiana at age seven, he attended school only sporadically, for a total of less than 12 months by age 15.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nevertheless, he was an avid reader and maintained a lifelong interest in learning.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Lincoln was a teenager his father relied heavily on him for farmwork and for supplementary income, hiring the boy out to area farmers and pocketing the money, as was the custom at the time.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] When he was somewhat older, Lincoln and some friends took a job carrying goods by flatboat to New Orleans, Louisiana, where the slave markets, according to the historian Michael Burlingame, "would leave an indelible impression on him....
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] In March 1830, fearing another milk-sickness outbreak, several members of the extended Lincoln family, including Abraham, moved west to Illinois and settled in Macon County.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Abraham became increasingly distant from Thomas, in part due to his father's lack of interest in education; he would later refuse to attend his father's deathbed or funeral in 1851.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Some historians, such as Michael Burlingame, identify Lincoln's first romantic interest as Ann Rutledge, a young woman also from Kentucky whom he met when he moved to New Salem, Illinois.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lewis Gannett disputes that the evidence supports a romantic relationship between the two.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] David Herbert Donald states that "How that friendship [between Lincoln and Rutledge] developed into a romance cannot be reconstructed from the record".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rutledge died on August 25, 1835, of typhoid fever.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln took her death very hard, sinking into a serious depression and contemplating suicide.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the early 1830s, Lincoln met Mary Owens from Kentucky.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Late in 1836, Lincoln agreed to marry Owens if she returned to New Salem.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Owens arrived that November and he courted her, but they both had second thoughts.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] On August 16, 1837, he wrote Owens a letter saying he would not blame her if she ended the relationship, and she declined to marry him.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1839, Lincoln met Mary Todd in Springfield, Illinois, and the following year they became engaged.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] She was a daughter of Robert Smith Todd, a wealthy lawyer and businessman in Lexington, Kentucky.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln initially broke off the engagement in early 1841, but the two were reconciled and married on November 4, 1842.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1844, the couple bought a house in Springfield near his law office.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] The marriage was turbulent; Mary was verbally abusive and at times physically violent towards her husband.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] The eldest, Robert Todd Lincoln, was born in 1843, and was the only child to live to maturity.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Edward Baker "Eddie" Lincoln, born in 1846, died February 1, 1850, probably of tuberculosis.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's third son, William Wallace "Willie" Lincoln, was born on December 21, 1850, and died of a fever at the White House on February 20, 1862.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] The youngest, Thomas "Tad" Lincoln, was born on April 4, 1853, and died of edema at age 18 on July 16, 1871.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln loved children, and the Lincolns were not considered to be strict with their own.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] The deaths of Eddie and Willie had profound effects on both parents.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln suffered from "melancholy", a condition now thought to be clinical depression.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1831, Lincoln's father moved the family to a new homestead in Coles County, Illinois, after which Abraham struck out on his own.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] He made his home in New Salem, Illinois, for six years.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] During 1831 and 1832, Lincoln worked at a general store in New Salem.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] He gained a reputation for strength and courage after winning a wrestling match with the leader of a group of ruffians known as the Clary's Grove boys.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1832, he declared his candidacy for the Illinois House of Representatives, though he interrupted his campaign to serve as a captain in the Illinois Militia during the Black Hawk War.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] He was elected the captain of his militia company but did not see combat.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his political campaigning, Lincoln advocated for navigational improvements on the Sangamon River.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] He drew crowds as a raconteur, but he lacked name recognition, powerful friends, and money, and he lost the election.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Lincoln returned home from the war, he planned to become a blacksmith but instead purchased a New Salem general store in partnership with William Berry.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Because a license was required to sell customers alcoholic beverages, Berry obtained bartending licenses for Lincoln and himself, and in 1833 the Lincoln–Berry General Store became a tavern as well.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Burlingame wrote that Berry was "an undisciplined, hard-drinking fellow", and Lincoln "was too soft-hearted to deny anyone credit".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Although the economy was booming, the business struggled and went into debt, prompting Lincoln to sell his share.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln served as New Salem's postmaster and later as county surveyor, but he continued his voracious reading and decided to become a lawyer.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rather than studying in the office of an established attorney, as was customary, Lincoln read law on his own, borrowing legal texts, including Blackstone's *Commentaries* and Chitty's *Pleadings*, from attorney John Todd Stuart.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] He later said of his legal education that he "studied with nobody." He was bestowed an honorary degree of Doctor of Laws by Columbia University in 1861.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] In Lincoln's second state house campaign in 1834, as a supporter of Whig Party leader Henry Clay, he finished second among thirteen candidates running for four places.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln echoed Clay's support for the American Colonization Society, which advocated abolition in conjunction with settling freed slaves in Liberia.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Whigs also favored economic modernization in banking, tariffs to fund internal improvements such as railroads, and urbanization.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln served four terms in the Illinois House of Representatives for Sangamon County.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] In this role, he championed construction of the Illinois and Michigan Canal.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln voted to expand suffrage beyond White landowners to all White men.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] He supported the chartering of the Illinois State Bank, and also led a successful campaign for moving the state capital from Vandalia to Springfield.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 27, 1838, Lincoln delivered an address at the Lyceum in Springfield, after the murder of the anti-slavery newspaper editor Elijah Parish Lovejoy.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] In this ostensibly non-partisan speech, Lincoln attacked Stephen A.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Douglas and the Democratic Party, who the Whigs argued were supporting "mobocracy".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] His speech also attacked anti-abolitionism and racial bigotry.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln was criticized in the press for a planned duel with James Shields, whom he had ridiculed in letters published under the name "Aunt Rebecca".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Although the duel did not take place, Burlingame noted that "the affair embarrassed Lincoln terribly".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1843, Lincoln sought the Whig nomination for Illinois's 7th district seat in the U.S.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Hardin was the winning candidate, though Lincoln convinced the party convention to limit Hardin to one term.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln not only gained the nomination in 1846, but also won the election.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] The only Whig in the Illinois delegation, he was assigned to the Committee on Post Office and Post Roads and the Committee on Expenditures in the War Department.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Giddings on a bill to abolish slavery in the District of Columbia, but dropped the bill when it failed to attract support from most other Whigs.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln spoke against the Mexican–American War (1846–1848), for which he said President James K.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Polk had "some strong motive ... to involve the two countries in a war, and trusting to escape scrutiny, by fixing the public gaze upon the exceeding brightness of military glory—that attractive rainbow, that rises in showers of blood".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] He supported the Wilmot Proviso, a failed 1846 proposal to ban slavery in any U.S. territory won from Mexico.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Polk insisted that Mexican soldiers had begun the war by "invading the territory of the State of Texas ... and shedding the blood of our citizens on our own soil".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his 1847 "spot resolutions", Lincoln rhetorically demanded that Polk tell Congress the exact "spot" where this occurred, but the Polk administration did not respond.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] His approach and rhetoric cost Lincoln political support in his district, and newspapers derisively nicknamed him "spotty Lincoln".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln had pledged in 1846 to serve only one term in the House.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] At the 1848 Whig National Convention, he initially supported Henry Clay and was among the leaders of the Illinois delegation backing Clay, voting for him on the early ballots.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] When it became clear that Clay could not secure the nomination, Lincoln joined other Whigs in shifting support to Zachary Taylor, who won the party's nomination and the presidency in 1848.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] After Taylor won, Lincoln hoped in vain to be appointed commissioner of the United States General Land Office.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] The administration offered to appoint him secretary of the Oregon Territory instead.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] This would have disrupted his legal and political career in Illinois, so he declined and resumed his law practice.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln was admitted to the Illinois bar on September 9, 1836.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] He moved to Springfield and began to practice law under John T.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] He partnered for several years with Stephen T.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Logan and, in 1844, began his practice with William Herndon.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his Springfield practice, according to Donald, Lincoln handled "virtually every kind of business that could come before a prairie lawyer".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] He dealt with many transportation cases in the midst of the nation's western expansion, particularly river barge conflicts under the new railroad bridges.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1849 he received a patent for a flotation device for the movement of riverboats in shallow water and Lincoln initially favored riverboat legal interests, but he represented whoever hired him.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] He represented a bridge company against a riverboat company in *Hurd v.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rock Island Bridge Company*, a landmark case involving a canal boat that sank after hitting a bridge.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] His patent was never commercialized, but it made Lincoln the only president to hold a patent.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln appeared before the Illinois Supreme Court in 411 cases.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] From 1853 to 1860, one of his largest clients was the Illinois Central Railroad, which Lincoln successfully sued to recover his legal fees.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln represented William "Duff" Armstrong in his 1858 trial for the murder of James Preston Metzker.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] The case is famous for Lincoln's use of a fact established by judicial notice to challenge the credibility of an eyewitness.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] After a witness testified to seeing the crime in the moonlight, Lincoln produced a *Farmers' Almanac* showing the Moon was at a low angle, drastically reducing visibility.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] In an 1859 murder case, he defended "Peachy" Quinn Harrison, the grandson of Peter Cartwright, Lincoln's political opponent.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Harrison was charged with the murder of Greek Crafton who, according to Cartwright, said as he lay dying that he had "brought it upon myself" and that he forgave Harrison.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln angrily protested the judge's initial decision to exclude Cartwright's claim as hearsay.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln argued that the testimony involved a dying declaration and so was not subject to the hearsay rule.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Instead of holding Lincoln in contempt of court as expected, the judge, a Democrat, admitted the testimony into evidence, resulting in Harrison's acquittal.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Compromise of 1850 failed to alleviate tensions over slavery between the slave-holding South and the free North.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] As the slavery debate in the Nebraska and Kansas territories became particularly acrimonious, Illinois Senator Stephen A.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Douglas proposed popular sovereignty as a compromise; the measure would allow the electorate of each territory to decide the status of slavery.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] The legislation alarmed many Northerners, who sought to prevent the spread of slavery, but Douglas's Kansas–Nebraska Act narrowly passed Congress in May 1854.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's Peoria Speech of October 1854, in which he declared his opposition to slavery, was one of an estimated 175 speeches he delivered in the next six years on the topic of excluding slavery from the territories.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's attacks on the Kansas–Nebraska Act marked his return to political life.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nationally, the Whigs were irreparably split by the Kansas–Nebraska Act and other ineffective efforts to compromise on the slavery issue.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Reflecting on the demise of his party, Lincoln wrote in 1855, "I think I am a whig; but others say there are no whigs, and that I am an abolitionist....
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] I now do no more than oppose the *extension* of slavery." The new Republican Party was formed as a northern party dedicated to anti-slavery, drawing from the anti-slavery wing of the Whig Party and combining Free Soil, Liberty, and anti-slavery Democratic Party members.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln resisted early Republican entreaties, fearing that the new party would become a platform for extreme abolitionists.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln held out hope for rejuvenating the Whigs, though he lamented his party's growing closeness with the nativist Know Nothing movement.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1854, Lincoln was elected to the Illinois legislature, but before the term began he declined to take his seat so that he would be eligible to run in the upcoming U.S.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] At that time, senators were elected by state legislatures.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] After leading in the first six rounds of voting, Lincoln was unable to obtain a majority.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln instructed his backers to vote for Lyman Trumbull, an anti-slavery Democrat who had received few votes in the earlier ballots.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's decision to withdraw enabled his Whig supporters and Trumbull's anti-slavery Democrats to combine and defeat the mainstream Democratic candidate, Joel Aldrich Matteson.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Violent political confrontations in Kansas continued, and opposition to the Kansas–Nebraska Act remained strong throughout the North.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] As the 1856 elections approached, Lincoln joined the Republicans and attended the Bloomington Convention, where the Illinois Republican Party was established.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] The convention platform endorsed Congress's right to regulate slavery in the territories and backed the admission of Kansas as a free state.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln gave the final speech of the convention, calling for the preservation of the Union.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] At the June 1856 Republican National Convention, Lincoln received support to run as vice president, but the party put forward a ticket of John C.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Frémont and William Dayton, which Lincoln supported throughout Illinois.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Democrats nominated James Buchanan and the Know Nothings nominated Millard Fillmore.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Buchanan prevailed, while Republican William Henry Bissell won election as Governor of Illinois, and Lincoln became a leading Republican in Illinois.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Dred Scott was a slave whose master took him from a slave state to a territory that was free as a result of the Missouri Compromise.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] After Scott was returned to the slave state, he petitioned a federal court for his freedom.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] His petition was denied in *Dred Scott v.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Taney wrote in his opinion that the Missouri Compromise was unconstitutional because it infringed on slave owners' property rights by prohibiting them from bringing their slaves into the territories.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] While many Democrats hoped that *Dred Scott* would end the dispute over slavery in the territories, the decision sparked further outrage in the North.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln denounced it as the product of a conspiracy of Democrats to support the Slave Power.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] He argued that the decision was at variance with the Declaration of Independence, which stated that "all men are created equal ... with certain unalienable rights", among them "life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1858, Douglas was up for re-election in the U.S.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Senate, and Lincoln hoped to defeat him.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Many in the party felt that a former Whig should be nominated in 1858, and Lincoln's 1856 campaigning and support of Trumbull had earned him a favor.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] For the first time, Illinois Republicans held a convention to agree upon a Senate candidate, and Lincoln won the nomination with little opposition.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln accepted the nomination with great enthusiasm and zeal.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] The speech created a stark image of the danger of disunion.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Senate campaign featured seven debates between Lincoln and Douglas; they had an atmosphere akin to a prizefight and drew thousands.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln warned that the Slave Power was threatening the values of republicanism, and he accused Douglas of distorting Jefferson's premise that all men are created equal.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his Freeport Doctrine, Douglas argued that, despite the *Dred Scott* decision, which he claimed to support, local settlers, under popular sovereignty, should be free to choose whether to allow slavery in their territory.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] He accused Lincoln of having joined the abolitionists.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Though the Republican legislative candidates won more popular votes, the Democrats won more seats, and the legislature re-elected Douglas.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] However, Lincoln's articulation of the issues had given him a national political presence.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the aftermath of the 1858 election, newspapers frequently mentioned Lincoln as a potential Republican presidential candidate.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] While Lincoln was popular in the Midwest, he lacked support in the Northeast and was unsure whether to seek the office.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] In January 1860, Lincoln told a group of political allies that he would accept the presidential nomination if offered and, in the following months, William O.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Stoddard's *Central Illinois Gazette*, the *Chicago Press & Tribune*, and other local papers endorsed his candidacy.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] In February 1860, Henry Ward Beecher invited Lincoln to address his congregation at Plymouth Church in Brooklyn, New York.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln agreed, but the venue shifted to Cooper Union in Manhattan.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Many in the audience thought he appeared awkward and even ugly.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] But Lincoln demonstrated intellectual leadership, which brought him into contention for the presidency.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Journalist Noah Brooks reported, "No man ever before made such an impression on his first appeal to a New York audience".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Historian David Herbert Donald described the speech as "a superb political move for an unannounced presidential aspirant." In response to an inquiry about his ambitions, Lincoln said, "The taste *is* in my mouth a little".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] On May 9–10, 1860, the Illinois Republican State Convention was held in Decatur.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Exploiting his embellished frontier legend of clearing land and splitting fence rails, Lincoln's supporters promoted him as "The Rail Candidate".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] On May 18 at the Republican National Convention in Chicago, Lincoln won the nomination on the third ballot.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] A former Democrat, Hannibal Hamlin of Maine, was nominated for vice president to balance the ticket.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Throughout the 1850s, Lincoln had doubted the prospects of civil war, and his supporters rejected claims that his election would incite secession.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Douglas was selected as the candidate of the Northern Democrats, delegates from the Southern slave states elected incumbent Vice President John C.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] A group of former Whigs and Know Nothings formed the Constitutional Union Party and nominated John Bell of Tennessee.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln and Douglas competed for votes in the North, while Bell and Breckinridge found support primarily in the South.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] A nationwide militaristic Republican youth organization, the Wide Awakes, "turned it into one of the most excited elections in American history" and "triggered massive popular enthusiasm", according to the political historian Jon Grinspan.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] People of the Northern states knew the Southern states would vote against Lincoln and rallied supporters for him.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] As Douglas and the other candidates campaigned, Lincoln gave no speeches, relying on the enthusiasm of the Republican Party.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Republican speakers emphasized Lincoln's childhood poverty to demonstrate the power of "free labor", which allowed a common farm boy to work his way to the top by his own efforts.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Though he did not make public appearances, many sought to visit and write to Lincoln.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the runup to the election, he took an office in the Illinois state capitol to deal with the influx of attention.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] He also hired John George Nicolay as his personal secretary, who would remain in that role during the presidency.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] On November 6, 1860, Lincoln was elected as the first Republican president.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] His victory was entirely due to his support in the North and West.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] No ballots were cast for him in 10 of the 15 Southern slave states.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln received 1,866,452 votes, or 39.8 percent of the total in a four-way race, carrying the free Northern states, as well as California and Oregon, and winning the electoral vote decisively.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] above the rotunda still under construction.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] following Lincoln's first inauguration portended imminent hostilities.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] After Lincoln's election, secessionists implemented plans to leave the Union before he took office in March 1861.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] On December 20, 1860, South Carolina adopted an ordinance of secession; by February 1, 1861, Florida, Mississippi, Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana, and Texas had followed.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Six of these states declared themselves to be a sovereign nation, the Confederate States of America, selecting Jefferson Davis as its provisional president.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] The upper South and border states (Delaware, Maryland, Virginia, North Carolina, Tennessee, Kentucky, Missouri, and Arkansas) initially rejected the secessionist appeal.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] President Buchanan and President-elect Lincoln refused to recognize the Confederacy, declaring secession illegal.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] On February 11, 1861, Lincoln gave a particularly emotional farewell address upon leaving Springfield for Washington.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and the Republicans rejected the proposed Crittenden Compromise as contrary to the party's platform of free-soil in the territories.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln said, "I will suffer death before I consent ... to any concession or compromise which looks like buying the privilege to take possession of this government to which we have a constitutional right".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln supported the Corwin Amendment to the U.S.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Constitution, which would have protected slavery in states where it already existed.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] The amendment passed Congress and was awaiting ratification by the required three-fourths of the states when Southern states began to secede.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] On March 4, 1861, in his first inaugural address, Lincoln said that, because he held "such a provision to now be implied constitutional law, I have no objection to its being made express, and irrevocable".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Due to secessionist plots, careful attention was paid to Lincoln's security and the train he took to Washington.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] The president-elect evaded suspected assassins in Baltimore.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] He traveled in disguise, wearing a soft felt hat instead of his customary stovepipe hat and draping an overcoat over his shoulders while hunching to conceal his height.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] On February 23, 1861, he arrived in Washington, D.C., which was placed under military guard.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Many in the opposition press criticized his secretive journey; opposition newspapers mocked Lincoln with caricatures showing him sneaking into the capital.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] The president ended his address with an appeal to the people of the South: "We are not enemies, but friends....
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] The mystic chords of memory, stretching from every battle-field, and patriot grave, to every living heart and hearthstone ... will yet swell the chorus of the Union, when again touched ... by the better angels of our nature".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Donald, the failure of the Peace Conference of 1861 to attract the attendance of seven of the Confederate states signaled that legislative compromise was not a practical expectation.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] In selecting his cabinet, Lincoln chose the men he found the most competent, even when they had been his opponents for the presidency.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln commented on his thought process, "We need the strongest men of the party in the Cabinet.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] We needed to hold our own people together.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] I had looked the party over and concluded that these were the very strongest men.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Then I had no right to deprive the country of their services." Doris Kearns Goodwin described the group in her 2005 biography of Lincoln as a "team of rivals".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln named his main political opponent, William H.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln made five appointments to the Supreme Court.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Noah Haynes Swayne, a prominent corporate lawyer from Ohio, replaced John McLean after the latter's death in April 1861.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Samuel Freeman Miller, who replaced Peter V.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Daniel, was an avowed abolitionist and received widespread support from Iowa politicians.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] David Davis was Lincoln's campaign manager in 1860 and had served as a judge in the Illinois court circuit where Lincoln practiced.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Democrat Stephen Johnson Field, a previous California Supreme Court justice, provided geographic and political balance.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Taney, Lincoln appointed his former secretary of the treasury, Salmon P.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Chase, to replace Taney as chief justice.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln believed Chase was an able jurist who would support Reconstruction legislation and that his appointment would unite the Republican Party.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early April 1861, Major Robert Anderson, commander of Fort Sumter in Charleston, South Carolina, advised that he was nearly out of food.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] After considerable deliberation, Lincoln decided to send provisions; according to Michael Burlingame, he "could not be sure that his decision would precipitate a war, though he had good reason to believe that it might".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] On April 12, 1861, Confederate forces fired on Union troops at Fort Sumter, starting the American Civil War.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] The April 12 and 13 attack on Fort Sumter rallied the Northern public to see military action against the South as necessary to defend the nation.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] On April 15, Lincoln called for 75,000 militiamen to recapture forts, protect Washington, and preserve the Union.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] This call forced states to choose whether to secede or to support the Union.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] North Carolina, Virginia, Tennessee, and Arkansas seceded.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] As the Northern states sent regiments south, on April 19 Baltimore mobs in control of the rail links attacked Union troops who were changing trains.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Local leaders' groups later burned critical rail bridges to the capital and the Army responded by arresting local Maryland officials.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln suspended the writ of *habeas corpus*, allowing arrests without formal charges.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] John Merryman, a Maryland officer arrested for hindering U.S. troop movements, successfully petitioned Supreme Court Chief Justice Taney to issue a writ of *habeas corpus*.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] In an opinion titled *Ex parte Merryman*, Taney, not ruling on behalf of the Supreme Court, wrote that the Constitution authorized only Congress and not the president to suspend habeas corpus.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] But Lincoln engaged in nonacquiescence and persisted with the policy of suspension in select areas.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Under various suspensions, 15,000 civilians were detained without trial; several, including the anti-war Democrat Clement L.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Vallandigham, were tried in military courts for "treasonable" actions, which was condemned as an attack on free speech.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln took executive control of the war and shaped the Union military strategy.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] He responded to the unprecedented political and military crisis as commander-in-chief by exercising unprecedented authority.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] He expanded his war powers, imposed a naval blockade on Confederate ports, disbursed funds before appropriation by Congress, suspended *habeas corpus*, and arrested and imprisoned thousands of suspected Confederate sympathizers.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln gained the support of Congress and the northern public for these actions.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also had to reinforce Union sympathies in the border slave states and keep the war from becoming an international conflict.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] It was clear from the outset that bipartisan support was essential to success, and that any compromise alienated factions in both political parties.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Copperheads (anti-war Democrats) criticized Lincoln for refusing to compromise on slavery; the Radical Republicans, who demanded harsh treatment against secession, criticized him for moving too slowly to abolish slavery.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] On August 6, 1861, Lincoln signed the Confiscation Act, which authorized judicial proceedings to confiscate and free slaves who were used to support the Confederates.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] The law had little practical effect, but it signaled political support for abolishing slavery.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's war strategy had two priorities: ensuring that Washington was well defended and conducting an aggressive war effort for a prompt, decisive victory.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Twice a week, Lincoln met with his cabinet.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Occasionally, Lincoln's wife, Mary, prevailed on him to take a carriage ride, concerned that he was working too hard.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Early in the war, Lincoln selected civilian generals from varied political and ethnic backgrounds "to secure their and their constituents' support for the war effort and ensure that the war became a national struggle".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] In January 1862, after complaints of inefficiency and profiteering in the War Department, Lincoln replaced Simon Cameron as secretary of war with Edwin Stanton.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stanton worked more often and more closely with Lincoln than did any other senior official.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Stanton's biographers Benjamin P.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Thomas and Harold Hyman, "Stanton and Lincoln virtually conducted the war together".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln saw the importance of Vicksburg for control of the Mississippi River valley and understood the necessity of defeating the enemy's army, rather than merely capturing territory.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] In directing the Union's war strategy, Lincoln valued the advice of Winfield Scott, even after his retirement as Commanding General of the United States Army.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] In 1861 Scott proposed the Anaconda Plan, which relied on port blockades and advancing down the Mississippi to subdue the South.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] In June 1862, Lincoln made an unannounced visit to West Point, where he spent five hours consulting with Scott regarding the handling of the war.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Internationally, Lincoln wanted to forestall foreign military aid to the Confederacy.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] He relied on his combative Secretary of State William Seward while working closely with Senate Foreign Relations Committee chairman Charles Sumner.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Navy illegally intercepted a British mail ship, the *RMS Trent*, on the high seas and seized two Confederate envoys.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Although the North celebrated the seizure, Britain protested vehemently, and the Trent Affair threatened war between the Americans and the British.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ended the crisis by releasing the two diplomats.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the Union rout at Bull Run and Winfield Scott's retirement, Lincoln appointed George B.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Early in the war, McClellan created defenses for Washington that were almost impregnable: 48 forts and batteries, with 480 guns manned by 7,200 artillerists.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] He spent months planning his Virginia Peninsula Campaign.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] McClellan's slow progress and excessive precautions frustrated Lincoln.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] McClellan, in turn, blamed the failure of the campaign on Lincoln's cautiousness in having reserved troops for the capital.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] In 1862, Lincoln removed McClellan as general-in-chief; he elevated Henry Halleck to the post and appointed John Pope as head of the new Army of Virginia.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] In the summer of 1862 Pope was soundly defeated at the Second Battle of Bull Run, forcing him to retreat to Washington.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Soon after, the Army of Virginia was disbanded.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Despite his dissatisfaction with McClellan's failure to reinforce Pope, Lincoln restored him to command of all forces around Washington, which included both the Army of the Potomac and the remains of the Army of Virginia.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lee's forces crossed the Potomac River into Maryland, leading to the Battle of Antietam.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] This battle, a Union victory, was among the bloodiest in American history.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] A crisis of command occurred for Lincoln when McClellan then resisted the president's demand that he pursue Lee's withdrawing army, while Don Carlos Buell likewise refused orders to move the Army of the Ohio against rebel forces in eastern Tennessee.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln replaced Buell with William Rosecrans and McClellan with Ambrose Burnside; according to Donald, this was a "shrewd" political move as they were non-partisan—unlike McClellan, a Democrat.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Against presidential advice, Burnside launched an offensive across the Rappahannock River and was defeated by Lee at Fredericksburg in December.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Facing low morale and discontent among the troops, Lincoln replaced Burnside with Joseph Hooker.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hooker endured heavy casualties at the Battle of Chancellorsville in May, then resigned in June and was replaced by George Meade.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Meade followed Lee north into Pennsylvania and defeated him in the Gettysburg campaign but then failed to effectively block Lee's orderly retreat to Virginia, despite Lincoln's demands.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant captured Vicksburg and gained control of the Mississippi River.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] In May 1863, Lincoln issued the Lieber Code, which governed wartime conduct of the Union Army, defining command responsibility for war crimes and crimes against humanity.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Two Union generals had issued emancipation orders in 1861 and 1862, but Lincoln overrode both: he found that the decision to emancipate was not within the generals' power, and that it might induce loyal border states to secede.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, in June 1862, Congress passed an act banning slavery in all federal territories, which Lincoln signed.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] In July, the Confiscation Act of 1862 was enacted, allowing the seizure of slaves from those disloyal to the United States.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] On July 22, 1862, Lincoln reviewed a draft of the Emancipation Proclamation with his cabinet.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Senator Willard Saulsbury Sr. criticized the proclamation, stating that it "would light their author to dishonor through all future generations".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] By contrast, Horace Greeley, editor of the *New-York Tribune*, in his public letter, "The Prayer of Twenty Millions", implored Lincoln to embrace emancipation.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Buttressed by news of the recent Union victory at Antietam, on September 22, 1862, Lincoln issued the preliminary Emancipation Proclamation, which proclaimed that, on January 1, 1863, all persons held as slaves within any state still in rebellion would be free.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] On January 1, 1863, he issued the final Emancipation Proclamation, freeing the slaves in the ten states not then under Union control, exempting areas under such control.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] With the abolition of slavery in the rebel states now a military objective, Union armies advancing south enabled thousands to escape bondage.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Proclamation was immediately denounced by Copperheads, who advocated restoring the union by allowing slavery.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] It was also seen as a betrayal of his promise to Southern Unionists not to tamper with slavery; Emerson Etheridge, then Clerk of the House of Representatives, joined an unsuccessful plot to give the Democrats and Southern Unionists control of the House.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a result of the Proclamation, enlisting freedmen became official policy.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] In a letter to Tennessee military governor Andrew Johnson, Lincoln wrote, "The bare sight of fifty thousand armed, and drilled black soldiers on the banks of the Mississippi would end the rebellion at once".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln gave the dedication for the Gettysburg battlefield cemetery on November 19, 1863.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] The address became the most quoted speech in American history.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Following Admiral David Farragut's capture of New Orleans in 1862, and after victories at Gettysburg and Vicksburg, Lincoln proclaimed a national Thanksgiving holiday, to be celebrated on the final Thursday of November 1863.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's victories at the Battle of Shiloh and in the Vicksburg campaign impressed Lincoln.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Responding to criticism of Grant after Shiloh, Lincoln said, "I can't spare this man.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] He fights." Following Meade's failure to capture Lee's army after Gettysburg and after Grant's success at Chattanooga, Lincoln promoted Grant to commander of all Union armies.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln reacted to Union losses by mobilizing support throughout the North.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Union forces targeted infrastructure—plantations, railroads, and bridges—to weaken the South's morale and fighting ability.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] While Lincoln sanctioned this approach, he emphasized the defeat of the Confederate armies over destruction for its own sake.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's bloody Overland Campaign turned into a strategic success for the Union despite a number of setbacks.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] But the campaign was the bloodiest in American history: approximately 55,000 casualties on the Union side (including 7,600 deaths), compared to about 33,000 on the Confederate (including 4,200 deaths).
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lee's losses, although lower in absolute numbers, were proportionately higher (over 50%) than Grant's (about 45%).
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early April, the Confederate government evacuated Richmond and Lincoln visited the conquered capital.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Amid the turmoil of military actions, on June 30, 1864, Lincoln signed into law the Yosemite Grant, which provided unprecedented federal protection for the area now known as Yosemite National Park.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and Secretary of the Treasury Salmon Chase faced a challenge in funding a wartime economy.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congress quickly approved Lincoln's request to assemble an army, even increasing his proposed 400,000 soldiers to 500,000, but both Congress and Chase initially resisted raising taxes.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the Union defeat at the First Battle of Bull Run, which collapsed the bond market, Congress passed the Revenue Act of 1861.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] This act imposed the first U.S. federal income tax, creating a flat tax of three percent on annual incomes above $800 ($28,700 in current dollars).
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] As the average urban worker made approximately $600 per year, many were not required to pay income taxes.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also signed increases to the Morrill Tariff, which had become law in the final months of Buchanan's tenure.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] These tariffs raised import duties considerably and were designed both to increase revenue and to help manufacturers offset the burden of new taxes.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Throughout the war, Congress debated whether to raise additional revenue primarily by increasing tariff rates, which most strongly affected rural areas, or by increasing income taxes, which most affected wealthier individuals; the latter view proved more popular.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] The revenue measures of 1861 proved inadequate for funding the war, forcing Congress to take further action.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] In February 1862, Congress passed the Legal Tender Act, which authorized the minting of $150 million in "greenbacks"—the first banknotes issued by the U.S. government since the end of the American Revolution.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Greenbacks were not backed by gold or silver, but rather by the government's promise to honor their value.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] By the end of the war, $450 million worth of greenbacks were in circulation.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congress also passed the Revenue Act of 1862, which established an excise tax affecting nearly every commodity, as well as the first national inheritance tax.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] It also added a progressive tax structure to the federal income tax.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] To collect these taxes, Congress created the Office of the Commissioner of Internal Revenue.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Despite the new revenue measures, funding the war remained challenging.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] The government continued to issue greenbacks and borrow large amounts of money, and the U.S. national debt grew from $65 million in 1860 to over $2 billion in 1866.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Revenue Act of 1864 represented a compromise between those who favored a more progressive tax structure and those who favored a flat tax.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] It established a five-percent tax on incomes above $600 and a ten-percent tax on incomes above $10,000, and it raised taxes on businesses.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early 1865, Congress reduced the threshold for ten-percent taxation to incomes above $5000.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] By the end of the war, the income tax constituted about one-fifth of the federal government's revenue, though it was intended as a temporary wartime measure.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also took action against wartime fraud, signing into law the False Claims Act of 1863.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] This statute imposed penalties for false claims and made it possible for private citizens to file false-claim (*qui tam*) lawsuits on behalf of the U.S. government and share in the recovery.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hoping to stabilize the currency, Lincoln convinced Congress to pass the National Banking Act in 1863, established the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency to oversee "national banks," which were subject to federal, rather than state, regulation.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] In return for investing a third of their capital in federal bonds, national banks were authorized to issue federal banknotes.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] After Congress imposed a tax on private banknotes in March 1865, federal banknotes became the dominant form of paper currency.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Other economic policies passed under Lincoln included the 1862 Homestead Act, which made millions of acres of government-held land in the West available for purchase at low cost.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] The 1862 Morrill Land-Grant Colleges Act provided government grants for agricultural colleges in each state.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Pacific Railway Acts of 1862 and 1864 granted federal support for the construction of the United States' first transcontinental railroad, which was completed in 1869.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] At the start of the war, Russia was the lone great power to support the Union, while the other European powers had varying degrees of sympathy for the Confederacy.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to the historian Dean Mahin, Lincoln had "limited familiarity with diplomatic practices" but exerted "substantial influence on U.S. diplomacy" as the Union attempted to avoid war with Britain and France.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln appointed diplomats to try to persuade European nations not to recognize the Confederacy.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's policy succeeded: all foreign nations were officially neutral throughout the Civil War, with none recognizing the Confederacy.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Some European leaders looked for ways to exploit the inability of the U.S. to enforce the Monroe Doctrine opposing European colonial intervention in the Americas: Spain invaded the Dominican Republic in 1861, while France established a puppet regime in Mexico.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, many in Europe also hoped for a quick end to the war, both for humanitarian reasons and because of the economic disruption it caused.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] The European aristocracy was "absolutely gleeful in pronouncing the American debacle as proof that the entire experiment in popular government had failed", according to Don H.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Union diplomats initially had to explain that the United States was not committed to ending slavery, and instead they argued that secession was unconstitutional.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Confederate spokesmen were more successful by ignoring slavery and instead focusing on their struggle for independence, their commitment to free trade, and the essential role of cotton in the European economy.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Confederacy's hope that cotton exports would compel European interference did not come to fruition, as Britain found alternative sources and maintained economic ties with the Union.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Though the issuance of the Emancipation Proclamation in January 1863 did not immediately end the possibility of European intervention, it rallied European public opinion to the Union by adding abolition as a Union war goal.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Any chance of a European intervention in the war ended with the Union victories at Gettysburg and Vicksburg in July 1863, as European leaders came to believe that the Confederate cause was doomed.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Dole as commissioner of the Bureau of Indian Affairs and made "extensive use of Indian Service positions to reward political supporters", according to the historian Thomas Britten.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's policies largely focused on assimilation of Native Americans and diminishing tribal landholdings, consistent with those of his predecessors, but his direct involvement in Native American affairs was unclear.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] His administration faced difficulties guarding Western settlers, railroads, and telegraph lines from Native American attacks.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Tensions arose with the Dakota people due to American treaty violations, unfair trading, and government practices that led to starvation.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] In August 1862, the Dakota War broke out in Minnesota.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hundreds of settlers were killed and 30,000 were displaced from their homes.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Some feared incorrectly that it might represent a Confederate conspiracy to start a war on the Northwestern frontier.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ordered thousands of paroled prisoners of war be sent to put down the uprising.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] When the Confederacy protested, Lincoln revoked the policy and none arrived in Minnesota.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln sent Pope as commander of the new Department of the Northwest.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Appointed as a state militia colonel, Henry Hastings Sibley eventually defeated the Dakota chief Little Crow at the Battle of Wood Lake.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] A war crimes trial led by Sibley sentenced 303 Dakota warriors to death; the legal scholar Carol Chomsky described the trial as "a study in military injustice" designed to "guarantee an unjust outcome".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln pardoned all but 39 of the condemned warriors, and, with one execution suspended, the remaining 38 were hanged in the largest mass execution in U.S. history.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congressman Alexander Ramsey told Lincoln in 1864 that he would have received more re-election support in Minnesota had he executed all 303 warriors.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln responded, "I could not afford to hang men for votes." Lincoln called for reform of federal Indian policy but prioritized the war and Reconstruction.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Changes were made in response to the Sand Creek Massacre of November 1864, prioritizing peaceful administration of Native affairs and condemning those encroaching on Native territory, but not until after Lincoln's death.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ran for re-election in 1864; the Democratic nominee was former general McClellan.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Republican Party selected Andrew Johnson, a War Democrat, as Lincoln's running mate.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] To broaden his coalition to include War Democrats as well as Republicans, Lincoln ran under the new label of the National Union Party.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's bloody stalemates and Confederate victories such as the Battle of the Crater damaged Lincoln's re-election prospects, and many Republicans feared defeat.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln prepared a confidential memorandum pledging that, if he should lose the election, he would "co-operate with the President-elect, as to save the Union between the election and the inauguration; as he will have secured his election on such ground that he cannot possibly save it afterwards".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Victories at Atlanta in September and in the Shenandoah Valley in October turned public opinion, and Lincoln was re-elected with 55.1 percent of the popular vote as well as 212 electoral votes to McClellan's 21.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] As Grant continued to weaken Lee's forces, efforts to discuss peace began.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stephens, the Confederate vice president, and two other Confederate officials met with Lincoln and Seward at Hampton Roads.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln refused to negotiate with the Confederacy as a coequal, and the only agreement reached at the meeting concerned the exchange of prisoners.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's second inauguration took place on March 4, 1865; historian Mark Noll places his second inaugural address "among the small handful of semi-sacred texts by which Americans conceive their place in the world"; it is inscribed in the Lincoln Memorial.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] A month later, on April 9, Lee surrendered to Grant at Appomattox, signaling the end of the war.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] It triggered a series of subsequent surrenders across the South—in North Carolina, Alabama, and the trans-Mississippi Theater—and finally at sea with the surrender of the CSS *Shenandoah* in November 1865.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Reconstruction began before the war's end, as Lincoln and his associates considered the reintegration of the nation, and the fates of Confederate leaders and freed slaves.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] When a general asked Lincoln how the defeated Confederates were to be treated, Lincoln replied, "Let 'em up easy"; he focused not on blame for the war but on rebuilding.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Determined to reunite the nation and not alienate the South, Lincoln urged that speedy elections under generous terms be held.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] His Amnesty Proclamation of December 8, 1863, offered pardons to those who had not held a Confederate civil office and had not mistreated Union prisoners, if they signed an oath of allegiance.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln led the moderates in Reconstruction policy and was opposed by the Radicals, under Thaddeus Stevens, Charles Sumner and Benjamin Wade, who otherwise remained Lincoln's allies.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] As Southern states fell, they needed leaders while their administrations were being restored.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] In Tennessee and Arkansas, Lincoln appointed Andrew Johnson and Frederick Steele, respectively, as military governors.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] In Louisiana, Lincoln ordered Nathaniel P.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Banks to promote a plan that would reestablish statehood when 10 percent of the voters agreed, but only if the reconstructed states abolished slavery.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Democratic opponents accused Lincoln of using the plan to ensure his and the Republicans' political aspirations.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Radicals denounced his policy as too lenient and passed their own plan, the 1864 Wade–Davis Bill, but Lincoln pocket-vetoed it.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Radicals retaliated by refusing to seat elected representatives from Louisiana, Arkansas, and Tennessee.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] After implementing the Emancipation Proclamation, Lincoln increased pressure on Congress to outlaw slavery nationwide with a constitutional amendment.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] By December 1863 an amendment was brought to Congress.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Senate passed it on April 8, 1864, but the first vote in the House of Representatives fell short of the required two-thirds majority.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Passage became part of Lincoln's re-election platform, and after his re-election, the second attempt in the House passed on January 31, 1865.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] After ratification by three-fourths of the states in December 1865, it became the Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution, abolishing "slavery [and] involuntary servitude, except as a punishment for crime".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln announced a Reconstruction plan that involved short-term military administration, pending readmission under the control of southern Unionists.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] He also signed Senator Charles Sumner's Freedmen's Bureau bill that set up a temporary federal agency designed to meet the immediate needs of former slaves.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] The law opened land for a lease of three years with the ability for the freedmen to purchase title.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Eric Foner argues that "Lincoln did not see Reconstruction as an opportunity for a sweeping political and social revolution beyond emancipation.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] He had long made clear his opposition to the confiscation and redistribution of land." However, the Lincoln scholar Phillip S.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Paludan suggests that at the end of his life Lincoln was moving towards a more radical position, particularly with regards to freedmen's rights.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] John Wilkes Booth was a well-known actor and a Confederate spy from Maryland; although he never joined the Confederate army, he had contacts within the Confederate secret service.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] After attending Lincoln's last public address, on April 11, 1865, in which Lincoln stated his preference that the franchise be conferred on some Black men, specifically "on the very intelligent, and on those who serve our cause as soldiers", Booth plotted to assassinate the President.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] When Booth learned of the Lincolns' intent to attend a play with Grant, he planned to assassinate Lincoln and Grant at Ford's Theatre.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and his wife attended the play *Our American Cousin* on the evening of April 14.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] At the last minute, Grant decided to go to New Jersey to visit his children instead.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] At 10:15 pm, Booth entered Lincoln's theater box, crept up from behind, and fired at the back of Lincoln's head, mortally wounding him.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's guest, Major Henry Rathbone, momentarily grappled with Booth, but Booth stabbed him and escaped.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] After being attended by Charles Leale and two other doctors, Lincoln was taken across the street to Petersen House.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] He remained in a coma for nine hours and died at 7:22 am on April 15.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's body was wrapped in a flag and placed in a coffin, which was loaded into a hearse and escorted to the White House by Union soldiers.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Johnson was sworn in as president later that day.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Two weeks later, Booth was located, shot, and killed at a farm in Virginia by Sergeant Boston Corbett.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] From April 19 to 20, Lincoln lay in state, first in the White House and then in the Capitol rotunda.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] The caskets containing Lincoln's body and the body of his third son Willie then traveled for two weeks on a funeral train following a circuitous route from Washington D.C. to Springfield, Illinois, stopping at several cities for memorials attended by hundreds of thousands.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Many others gathered along the tracks as the train passed with bands, bonfires, and hymn singing or in silent grief.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Historians emphasized the widespread shock and sorrow, but noted that some who had hated Lincoln celebrated his death.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Walt Whitman composed four elegies to Lincoln, including "When Lilacs Last in the Dooryard Bloom'd" and "O Captain!
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's body was buried at Oak Ridge Cemetery in Springfield and now lies within the Lincoln Tomb.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln redefined the political philosophy of republicanism in the United States.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Because the Declaration of Independence says that all men have an unalienable right to life, liberty and the pursuit of happiness, he called it the "sheet anchor" of republicanism, at a time when the Constitution was the focus of most political discourse.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] He presented the Declaration as establishing equality as a foundational principle for the United States, which had a significant impact on social and political movements in the U.S. into the 20th century.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a Whig activist, Lincoln was a spokesman for business interests, favoring high tariffs, banks, infrastructure improvements, and railroads, in opposition to Jacksonian democrats.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Nevertheless, Lincoln admired Andrew Jackson's steeliness and patriotism, and adopted the Jacksonian "belief in the common man".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a young man, Lincoln was a religious skeptic.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, he was deeply familiar with the Bible; throughout his public career, he often quoted scripture.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] His three most famous speeches—the House Divided Speech, the Gettysburg Address, and his second inaugural address—all contain such quotes.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] In the 1840s, Lincoln subscribed to the Doctrine of Necessity, a belief that the human mind was controlled by a higher power.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the death of his son Edward in 1850, Lincoln more frequently expressed a dependence on God.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] He never joined a church, although he and his wife frequently attended First Presbyterian Church in Springfield, Illinois, beginning in 1852.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] While president, Lincoln often attended services at the New York Avenue Presbyterian Church in Washington, D.C.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] The death of his son Willie in February 1862 may have caused him to look toward religion for solace.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's frequent use of religious imagery and language toward the end of his life may have reflected his own personal beliefs or might have been a device to reach his audiences, who were mostly evangelical Protestants.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Sources differ in how they describe his religious beliefs.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stephen Mansfield describes "an atheist or religiously skeptical Lincoln" as "the prevailing view", although he argues that "there was a spiritual journey of some kind in Abraham Lincoln's life".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Richard Carwardine writes that "Many elements of the inner Lincoln, including his personal faith ... necessarily remain a puzzle".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's last words were, as reported by his wife, "There is no place I so much desire to see as Jerusalem".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Michael Burlingame, Lincoln was described as "awkward" and "gawky" as a youth.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] In adolescence he was tall and strong, participating in jumping, throwing, wrestling, and footraces, and demonstrating exceptional strength.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Burlingame notes that Lincoln's clothes "were typically rough and suited to the frontier", with a gap between his shoes, socks, and pants that often exposed six or more inches of his shin; "he cared little about fashion".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln was a slender six feet four inches, with a high-pitched voice.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] While he is usually portrayed bearded, he did not grow a beard until 1860 at the suggestion of 11-year-old Grace Bedell; he was the first U.S. president to do so.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Herndon described Lincoln's face as "long, narrow, sallow, and cadaverous", his cheeks as "leathery and saffron-colored".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln described himself as having a "dark complexion, with coarse black hair".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Although Lincoln's features were said to be "unpleasant to behold," Walt Whitman "wrote that Lincoln's face was 'so awful ugly it becomes beautiful.'" Lincoln's detractors also remarked on his appearance.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Among the illnesses that Lincoln is either documented or speculated to have suffered from are depression, smallpox, and malaria.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] He took blue mass pills, which contained mercury, to treat melancholy or hypochondriasis; this could have resulted in mercury poisoning.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] Several claims have been made that Lincoln's health was declining before his assassination, as photographs of Lincoln appear to show weight loss and facial changes.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p02] It has been proposed that he could have had a rare genetic disorder such as Marfan syndrome or multiple endocrine neoplasia type 2B.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p03] In surveys of U.S. scholars ranking presidents since 1948, the top three presidents are generally Lincoln, George Washington, and Franklin D.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p03] A 2004 study found that scholars in history and politics ranked Lincoln number one, while legal scholars placed him second after Washington.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p03] Kennedy, and Ronald Reagan were the top-ranked presidents in eight public opinion surveys by Gallup.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln's assassination made him a national martyr.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p03] He was viewed by abolitionists as a champion of human liberty.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p03] Many, though not all, in the South considered Lincoln to be a man of outstanding ability.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p03] In the New Deal era, liberals honored Lincoln as an advocate of the common man who they claimed would have supported the welfare state, and Lincoln became a favorite of liberal intellectuals across the world.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p03] The high point came in 1922 with the dedication of the Lincoln Memorial on the National Mall in Washington, D.C.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p03] The Black orator and former slave Frederick Douglass stated that in "his company, I was never reminded of my humble origin, or of my unpopular color", and Lincoln has long been known as the Great Emancipator.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p03] By the late 1960s, some Black intellectuals denied that Lincoln deserved that title.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lerone Bennett Jr. won wide attention when he called Lincoln a White supremacist in 1968.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p03] He noted that Lincoln used ethnic slurs and argued that Lincoln opposed social equality and proposed that freed slaves voluntarily move to another country.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p03] Defenders of Lincoln highlighted his condemnation of slavery and his contributions to its abolition, casting his delays and racist rhetoric as concessions to political necessity rather than reflections of his personal beliefs.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln has also been characterized as a folk hero and as "Honest Abe".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p03] David Herbert Donald opined in his 1996 biography that Lincoln was endowed with the personality trait of negative capability, attributed to extraordinary leaders who were "capable of being in uncertainties ... without any irritable reaching after fact and reason".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln has often been portrayed by Hollywood, almost always in a flattering light; the film historian Melvyn Stokes writes that "moviemakers have commonly used Lincoln primarily as a metaphor for ideas and values they approved".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln's portrait appears on two denominations of United States currency, the penny and the $5 bill.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p03] He appears on postage stamps across the world, including in Ghana, Honduras, China, Haiti, Nicaragua, Colombia, and Argentina.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p03] He has been memorialized in many town, city, and county names, including the capital of Nebraska.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p03] The United States Navy has named three vessels after Lincoln, including the *Nimitz*-class aircraft carrier USS *Abraham Lincoln* (CVN-72).
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p03] The Lincoln Memorial in Washington, D.C., is one of the most visited National Park Service sites in the country.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p03] Memorials in Springfield, Illinois, include the Abraham Lincoln Presidential Library and Museum, Lincoln's home, and his tomb.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p03] A carving of Lincoln appears with those of three other presidents on Mount Rushmore, which receives about 3 million visitors a year.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p03] A statue of Lincoln completed by Augustus Saint-Gaudens stands in Lincoln Park, Chicago, with recastings given as diplomatic gifts standing in Parliament Square, London, and Parque Lincoln, Mexico City.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p03] Several states commemorate "Presidents' Day" as "Washington–Lincoln Day".
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln has been extensively portrayed in media.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p03] Early works, such as *Abraham Lincoln's Clemency* (1910), attempted to mythologize him, emphasizing his mercifulness.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p03] Works from the Great Depression era, such as *Young Mr.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln* (1939), embellished his early struggles and folksiness.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p03] The 1938 play *Abe Lincoln in Illinois* won a Pulitzer Prize and was adapted in film.
[src:applejack-drink/abraham-lincoln-p03] After a marked decrease in film portrayals between 1941 and 1999, Daniel Day-Lewis won the Academy Award for Best Actor for his portrayal in *Lincoln*, a 2012 biographical film directed by Steven Spielberg.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Absinthe was created in the canton of Neuchâtel in Switzerland in the late 18th century by the French physician Pierre Ordinaire.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] It rose to great popularity as an alcoholic drink in late 19th- and early 20th-century France, particularly among Parisian artists and writers.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The consumption of absinthe was opposed by social conservatives and prohibitionists, partly due to its association with bohemian culture.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] From Europe and the Americas, notable absinthe drinkers included Ernest Hemingway, James Joyce, Lewis Carroll, Charles Baudelaire, Paul Verlaine, Arthur Rimbaud, and Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Absinthe has often been portrayed as a dangerously addictive psychoactive drug and hallucinogen, which gave birth to the term *absinthism*.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The chemical compound thujone, which is present in the spirit in trace amounts, was blamed for its alleged harmful effects.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] By 1915, absinthe had been banned in the United States and much of Europe, including France, the Netherlands, Belgium, Switzerland, and Austria-Hungary, though it has not been demonstrated to be any more dangerous than ordinary spirits.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Recent studies have shown that absinthe's psychoactive properties, apart from those attributable to its alcohol content, have been exaggerated.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Absinthe's revival began in the 1990s, following the adoption of modern European Union food and beverage laws that removed long-standing barriers to its production and sale.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] By the early 21st century, nearly 200 brands of absinthe were being produced in a dozen countries, most notably in France, Switzerland, Austria, Germany, the Netherlands, Spain, and the Czech Republic.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The French word *absinthe* can refer either to the alcoholic beverage, or less commonly, to the actual wormwood plant.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Absinthe is derived from the Latin *absinthium*, which in turn comes from the Greek ἀψίνθιον *apsínthion* 'wormwood'.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Some argue that the word means "undrinkable" in Greek, but it may instead be linked to the Persian root, in Persian called *spand* or *aspand* or the variant *esfand*, which meant *Peganum harmala*, also called Syrian rue in English, although it is not a variety of rue, another famously bitter herb.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] That *Artemisia absinthium* was commonly burned as a protective offering may suggest that its origins lie in the reconstructed Proto-Indo-European language root **spend*, meaning "to perform a ritual" or "make an offering".
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Whether the word was a borrowing from Persian into Greek, or from a common ancestor of both, is unclear.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Alternatively, the Greek word may originate in a pre-Greek substrate word, marked by the non-Indo-European consonant complex -νθ *-nth*.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Alternative spellings for absinthe include *absinth*, *absynthe*, and *absenta*.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] *Absinth* (without the final *e*) is a spelling variant most commonly applied to absinthes produced in central and eastern Europe, and is specifically associated with Bohemian-style absinthes.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The precise origin of absinthe is unclear.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The medical use of wormwood dates back to ancient Egypt and is mentioned in the Ebers Papyrus from around 1550 BC.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Wormwood extracts and wine-soaked wormwood leaves were used as remedies by the ancient Greeks.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Moreover, some evidence exists of a wormwood-flavoured wine in ancient Greece called *absinthites oinos*.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Lucretius' *De Rerum Natura* (I, 936–950) says that a drink containing wormwood was given as medicine to children in a cup with honey on the brim to make it drinkable.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The first evidence of absinthe, in the sense of a distilled spirit containing green anise and fennel, dates to the 18th century.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] According to popular legend, it began as an all-purpose patent remedy created by Dr.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Pierre Ordinaire, a French doctor living in Couvet, Switzerland, around 1792 (the exact date varies by account).
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Ordinaire's recipe was passed on to the Henriod sisters of Couvet, who sold it as a medicinal elixir.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] By other accounts, the Henriod sisters may have been making the elixir before Ordinaire's arrival.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] In either case, a certain Major Dubied acquired the formula from the sisters in 1797 and opened the first absinthe distillery named Dubied Père et Fils in Couvet with his son Marcellin and son-in-law Henry-Louis Pernod.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] In 1805, they built a second distillery in Pontarlier, France, under the company name Maison Pernod Fils.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Pernod Fils remained one of the most popular brands of absinthe until the drink was banned in France in 1914.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Absinthe's popularity grew steadily through the 1840s, when it was given to French troops in Algeria as a malaria preventive, and the troops brought home their taste for it.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Absinthe became so popular in bars, bistros, cafés, and cabarets by the 1860s that the hour of 5 pm was called *l'heure verte* 'the green hour'.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] It was favoured by all social classes, from the wealthy bourgeoisie to poor artists and ordinary working-class people.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] By the 1880s, mass production had caused the price to drop sharply, and the French were drinking 36 million litres (9,500,000 US gal) per year by 1910.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Absinthe was exported widely from France and Switzerland and attained some degree of popularity in other countries, including Spain, the United Kingdom, the United States, and the Czech Republic.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] It was never banned in Spain or Portugal, and its production and consumption have never ceased.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] It gained a temporary popularity spike during the early 20th century, corresponding with the Art Nouveau and Modernism aesthetic movements.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] New Orleans has a cultural association with absinthe and is credited as the birthplace of the Sazerac, perhaps the earliest absinthe cocktail.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The Old Absinthe House bar on Bourbon Street began selling absinthe in the first half of the 19th century.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Its Catalan lease-holder, Cayetano Ferrer, named it the Absinthe Room in 1874 due to the drink's popularity, which was served in the Parisian style.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] It was frequented by Mark Twain, Oscar Wilde, Franklin Delano Roosevelt, Aleister Crowley, and Frank Sinatra.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Absinthe became associated with violent crimes and social disorder, and one modern writer claims that this trend was spurred by fabricated claims and smear campaigns, which he claims were orchestrated by the temperance movement and the wine industry.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Edgar Degas's 1876 painting **The Absinthe Drinker** or **Glass of Absinthe** (**L'Absinthe**) can be seen at the Musée d'Orsay epitomising the popular view of absinthe addicts as sodden and benumbed, and Émile Zola described its effects in his novel *L'Assommoir*.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] In 1905, Swiss farmer Jean Lanfray murdered his wife and two children and then attempted to kill himself after drinking absinthe.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Lanfray had drunk a lot of wine and brandy before the killings, but that was overlooked or ignored, and blame for the murders was placed solely on his consumption of two glasses of absinthe.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The Lanfray murders were the tipping point in this hotly debated topic, and a subsequent petition collected more than 82,000 signatures to ban it in Switzerland.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] It was approved by voters, and the prohibition of absinthe was written into the Swiss constitution.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] In 1906, Belgium and Brazil banned the sale and distribution of absinthe although these were not the first countries to take such action.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] It had been banned as early as 1898 in the colony of the Congo Free State.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The Netherlands banned it in 1909, Switzerland in 1910, the United States in 1912, and France in 1914.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The prohibition of absinthe in France eventually led to the popularity of pastis, and to a lesser extent, ouzo, and other anise-flavoured spirits that do not contain wormwood.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Following the conclusion of the First World War, production of the Pernod Fils brand was resumed at the Banus distillery in Catalonia, Spain (where absinthe was still legal), but gradually declining sales saw the cessation of production in the 1960s.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] In Switzerland, the ban served only to drive the production of absinthe underground.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Clandestine home distillers produced colourless absinthe (*la Bleue*), which was easier to conceal from the authorities.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Many countries never banned absinthe, notably the United Kingdom, where it had never been as popular as in continental Europe.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] British importer BBH Spirits began to import Hill's Absinth from the Czech Republic in the 1990s, as the UK had never formally banned it, and this sparked a modern resurgence in its popularity.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] It began to reappear during a revival in the 1990s in countries where it was never banned.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Forms of absinthe available during that time consisted almost exclusively of Czech, Spanish, and Portuguese brands that were of recent origin, typically consisting of Bohemian-style products.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Connoisseurs considered these of inferior quality and not representative of the 19th-century spirit.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] In 2000, La Fée Absinthe became the first commercial absinthe distilled and bottled in France since the 1914 ban, but it is now one of dozens of brands that are produced and sold within France.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] In the Netherlands, the restrictions were challenged by Amsterdam wine seller Menno Boorsma in July 2004, thus confirming the legality of absinthe once again.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Similarly, Belgium lifted its long-standing ban on 1 January 2005 citing a conflict with the adopted food and beverage regulations of the single European Market.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] In Switzerland, the constitutional ban was repealed in 2000 during an overhaul of the national constitution although the prohibition was written into ordinary law instead.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] That law was later repealed, and absinthe was made legal on March 1, 2005.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The drink was never officially banned in Spain although it began to fall out of favour in the 1940s and almost vanished into obscurity.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Catalonia has seen a significant resurgence since 2007 when one producer established operations there.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Absinthe has never been illegal to import or manufacture in Australia although importation requires a permit under the Customs (Prohibited Imports) Regulation 1956 due to a restriction on importing any product containing oil of wormwood.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] In 2000, an amendment made all wormwood species prohibited herbs for food purposes under Food Standard 1.4.4.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Prohibited and Restricted Plants and Fungi.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] However, this amendment was found inconsistent with other parts of the pre-existing Food Code, and it was withdrawn in 2002 during the transition between the two codes, thereby continuing to allow absinthe manufacture and importation through the existing permit-based system.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] These events were erroneously reported by the media as it having been reclassified from a *prohibited* product to a *restricted* product.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] In 2007, the French brand Lucid became the first genuine absinthe to receive a Certificate of Label Approval for import into the United States since 1912, following independent efforts by representatives from Lucid and Kübler to overturn the long-standing U.S. ban.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] George Spirits of Alameda, California became the first brand of American-made absinthe produced in the United States since the ban.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Since that time, other micro-distilleries have started producing small batches in the United States.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The French Absinthe Ban of 1915 was repealed in May 2011 following petitions by the *Fédération Française des Spiritueux*, which represents French distillers, and the French Senate voted to repeal the prohibition in April 2011.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] In Switzerland, the village of Môtiers, Val-de-Travers, near Neuchâtel, became the focal point of production and promotion of the liquor after a ban of nearly 100 years was lifted.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The national *Maison de l'Absinthe* (House of Absinthe), with its attached museum, is located in the former courthouse where absinthe distillers were formerly prosecuted.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The 21st century has seen new types of absinthe, including various frozen preparations, that have become increasingly popular.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Most countries have no legal definition for absinthe, whereas the method of production and content of spirits such as whisky, brandy, and gin are globally defined and regulated.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Therefore, producers are at liberty to label a product as "absinthe" or "absinth" without regard to any specific legal definition or quality standards.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Producers of legitimate absinthes employ one of two historically defined processes to create the finished spirit – distillation or cold mixing.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] In the sole country (Switzerland) that does possess a legal definition of absinthe, distillation is the only permitted method of production.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Distilled absinthe employs a method of production similar to that of high-quality gin.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Botanicals are initially macerated in distilled base alcohol before being redistilled to exclude bitter principles, and impart the desired complexity and texture to the spirit.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The distillation of absinthe first yields a colourless distillate that leaves the alembic at around 72% ABV.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The distillate may be reduced and bottled clear, to produce a *Blanche* or *la Bleue* absinthe, or it may be coloured to create a *verte* using natural or artificial colouring.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Traditional absinthes obtain their green color strictly from the chlorophyll of whole herbs, which is extracted from the plants during the secondary maceration.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] This step involves steeping plants such as petite wormwood, hyssop, and melissa (among other herbs) in the distillate.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Chlorophyll from these herbs is extracted, giving the drink its famous green color.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] This step also provides a herbal complexity that is typical of high-quality absinthe.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The natural coloring process is critical for absinthe ageing since the chlorophyll remains chemically active.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The chlorophyll serves a similar role in absinthe as tannins do in wine or brown liquors.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] After the coloring process, the resulting product is diluted with water to the desired alcohol percentage.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The flavor of absinthe is said to improve materially with storage, and many distilleries, before the ban, aged their absinthe in settling tanks before bottling.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Many modern absinthes are produced using a cold-mix process.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] This inexpensive method of production does not involve distillation, and is regarded as inferior for the same reasons that give cause for cheaply compounded gin to be legally differentiated from distilled gin.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The cold mixing process involves the simple blending of flavouring essences and artificial colouring in commercial alcohol, in similar fashion to most flavoured vodkas and inexpensive liqueurs and cordials.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Some modern cold-mixed absinthes have been bottled at strengths approaching 90% ABV.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Others are presented simply as a bottle of plain alcohol with a small amount of powdered herbs suspended within it.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The lack of a formal legal definition in most countries to regulate the production and quality of absinthe has enabled cheaply made products to be falsely presented as traditional in production and composition.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] In Switzerland, the only country with a formal legal definition of absinthe, any absinthe product not obtained by maceration and distillation or coloured artificially cannot be sold as absinthe.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Absinthe is traditionally prepared from a distillation of neutral alcohol, various herbs, spices, and water.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Traditional absinthes were redistilled from a white grape spirit (or *eau de vie*), while lesser absinthes were more commonly made from alcohol from grains, beets, or potatoes.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The principal botanicals are grande wormwood, green anise, and florence fennel, which are often called "the holy trinity".
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Many other herbs may be used as well, such as petite wormwood (*Artemisia pontica* or Roman wormwood), hyssop, melissa, star anise, angelica, peppermint, coriander, and veronica.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] One early recipe was included in 1864's *The English and Australian Cookery Book*.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] It directed the maker to "Take of the tops of wormwood, four pounds; root of angelica, calamus aromaticus, aniseed, leaves of dittany, of each one ounce; alcohol, four gallons.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Macerate these substances during eight days, add a little water, and distil by a gentle fire, until two gallons are obtained.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Adding to absinthe's negative reputation in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, unscrupulous makers of the drink omitted the traditional colouring phase of production in favour of adding toxic copper salts to artificially induce a green tint.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] This practice may be responsible for some of the alleged toxicity historically associated with this beverage.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Many modern-day producers resort to other shortcuts, including the use of artificial food coloring to create the green color.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Additionally, at least some cheap absinthes produced before the ban were reportedly adulterated with poisonous antimony trichloride, reputed to enhance the louching effect.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Absinthe may also be naturally coloured pink or red using rose or hibiscus flowers.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] This was referred to as a *rose* (pink) or *rouge* (red) absinthe.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Only one historical brand of rose absinthe has been documented.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Absinthe was historically bottled at 45–74% ABV.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Some modern Franco–Suisse absinthes are bottled at up to 83% ABV, while some modern, cold-mixed bohemian-style absinthes are bottled at up to 89.9% ABV.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The modern-day interest in absinthe has spawned a rash of absinthe kits from sellers claiming they produce homemade absinthe.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Kits often call for soaking herbs in vodka or alcohol or adding a liquid concentrate to vodka or alcohol to create an ersatz absinthe.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Such practices usually yield a harsh substance that bears little resemblance to the genuine article and is considered inauthentic by any practical standard.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Some concoctions may even be dangerous, especially if they call for a potentially poisonous inclusion of herbs, oils, or extracts.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] In at least one documented case, a person suffered acute kidney injury after drinking 10 ml of pure wormwood oil.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] In baking and in preparing the classic New Orleans-style Sazerac cocktail, anise-flavored liqueurs and pastis have often been used as a substitute if absinthe is unavailable.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The traditional French preparation involves placing a sugar cube on top of a specially designed slotted spoon and placing the spoon on a glass filled with a measure of absinthe.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Iced water is poured or dripped over the sugar cube to mix the water into the absinthe.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The final preparation contains 1 part absinthe and 3–5 parts water.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] As water dilutes the spirit, those components with poor water solubility (mainly those from anise, fennel, and star anise) come out of solution and cloud the drink.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The resulting milky opalescence is called the *louche* (/luʃ/, French: 'opaque' or 'shady').
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The release of these dissolved essences coincides with a perfuming of herbal aromas and flavours that "blossom" or "bloom", and brings out subtleties that are otherwise muted within the neat spirit.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] This reflects what is perhaps the oldest and purest method of preparation, and is often referred to as the *French method*.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The *Bohemian method* is a recent invention that involves fire, and was not performed during absinthe's peak of popularity in the Belle Époque.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Like the French method, a sugar cube is placed on a slotted spoon over a glass containing one shot of absinthe.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The sugar is soaked in alcohol (usually more absinthe), and then set ablaze.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The flaming sugar cube is then dropped into the glass, thus igniting the absinthe.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Finally, a shot glass of water is added to douse the flames.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] This method tends to produce a stronger drink than the French method.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] A variant of the Bohemian method involves allowing the fire to extinguish on its own.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] This variant is sometimes referred to as "cooking the absinthe" or "the flaming green fairy".
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The origin of this burning ritual may borrow from a coffee and brandy drink that was served at Café Brûlot, in which a sugar cube soaked in brandy was set aflame.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Most experienced absintheurs do not recommend the Bohemian Method and consider it a modern gimmick, as it can destroy the absinthe flavour and present a fire hazard due to the unusually high alcohol content present in absinthe.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] In 19th-century Parisian cafés, upon receiving an order for absinthe, a waiter would present the patron with a dose of absinthe in a suitable glass, sugar, absinthe spoon, and a carafe of iced water.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] It was up to the patron to prepare the drink, as the inclusion or omission of sugar was strictly an individual preference, as was the amount of water used.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] As the popularity of the drink increased, additional accoutrements of preparation appeared, including the absinthe fountain, which was effectively a large jar of iced water with spigots, mounted on a lamp base.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] This lets drinkers prepare several drinks at once – and with a hands-free drip, patrons could socialise while louching a glass.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Although many bars served absinthe in standard glassware, several glasses were specifically designed for the French absinthe preparation ritual.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Absinthe glasses were typically fashioned with a dose line, bulge, or bubble in the lower portion denoting how much absinthe should be poured.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] One "dose" of absinthe ranged anywhere around 2–2.5 fluid ounces (60–75 ml).
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] In addition to being prepared with sugar and water, absinthe emerged as a popular cocktail ingredient in both the United Kingdom and the United States.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] By 1930, dozens of fancy cocktails that called for absinthe had been published in numerous credible bartender guides.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] One of the most famous of these libations is Ernest Hemingway's "Death in the Afternoon" cocktail, a tongue-in-cheek concoction that contributed to a 1935 collection of celebrity recipes.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The directions are: "Pour one jigger absinthe into a Champagne glass.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Add iced Champagne until it attains the proper opalescent milkiness.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Most categorical alcoholic beverages have regulations governing their classification and labelling, while those governing absinthe have always been conspicuously lacking.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] According to popular treatises from the 19th century, absinthe could be loosely categorised into several grades (*ordinaire*, *demi-fine*, *fine*, and *Suisse* – the latter does not denote origin), in order of increasing alcoholic strength and quality.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Many contemporary absinthe critics simply classify absinthe as *distilled* or *mixed*, according to its production method.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] And while the former is generally considered far superior in quality to the latter, an absinthe's simple claim of being 'distilled' makes no guarantee as to the quality of its base ingredients or the skill of its maker.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Absinthe that is artificially coloured or clear is aesthetically stable and can be bottled in clear glass.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] If naturally colored absinthe is exposed to light or air for a prolonged period, the chlorophyll gradually becomes oxidized, which has the effect of gradually changing the color from green to yellow green, and eventually to brown.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The colour of absinthe that has completed this transition was historically referred to as *feuille morte* ("dead leaf").
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] In the pre-ban era, this natural phenomenon was favourably viewed, for it confirmed the product in question was coloured naturally, and not artificially with potentially toxic chemicals.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Predictably, vintage absinthes often emerge from sealed bottles as distinctly amber in tint due to decades of slow oxidation.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Though this colour change presents no adverse impact to the flavour of absinthe, it is generally desired to preserve the original colour, which requires that naturally coloured absinthe be bottled in dark, light-resistant bottles.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Absinthe intended for decades of storage should be kept in a cool (room temperature), dry place, away from light and heat.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Absinthe should not be stored in the refrigerator or freezer, as the anethole may polymerise inside the bottle, creating an irreversible precipitate, and adversely impacting the original flavour.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Absinthe has been frequently described in modern times as being hallucinogenic, a claim refuted by modern science.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The belief that absinthe induces hallucinogenic effects is rooted, at least partly, in the findings of 19th-century French psychiatrist Valentin Magnan, who carried out ten years of experiments with wormwood oil.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] In the course of this research, he studied 250 cases of alcoholism and concluded that those who abused absinthe were worse off than those who abused other alcoholic drinks, experiencing rapid-onset hallucinations.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Such accounts by opponents of absinthe (like Magnan) were cheerfully embraced by famous absinthe drinkers, many of whom were bohemian artists or writers.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Two famous artists who helped popularise the notion that absinthe had powerful psychoactive properties were Toulouse-Lautrec and Vincent van Gogh.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] In one of the best-known written accounts of absinthe drinking, an inebriated Oscar Wilde described a phantom sensation of having tulips brush against his legs after leaving a bar at closing time.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Notions of absinthe's alleged hallucinogenic properties were again fuelled in the 1970s when a scientific paper suggested that thujone's structural similarity to tetrahydrocannabinol (THC), the active chemical in cannabis, presented the possibility of THC receptor affinity.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Counterevidence to this was published in 1999.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The debate over whether absinthe produces effects on the human mind in addition to those of alcohol has not been resolved conclusively.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The effects of absinthe have been described by some as mind-opening.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The most commonly reported experience is a "clear-headed" feeling of inebriation – a form of "lucid drunkenness".
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Chemist, historian, and absinthe distiller Ted Breaux has claimed that the alleged secondary effects of absinthe may be because some of the herbal compounds in the drink act as stimulants, while others act as sedatives, creating an overall lucid effect of awakening.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The long-term effects of moderate absinthe consumption in humans remain unknown, although herbs traditionally used to produce absinthe are reported to have both painkilling and antiparasitic properties.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Today it is known that absinthe does not cause hallucinations.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] It was once widely promoted that excessive absinthe drinking caused effects that were discernible from those associated with alcoholism, a belief that led to the coining of the term *absinthism*.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] One of the first vilifications of absinthe followed an 1864 experiment in which Magnan simultaneously exposed one guinea pig to large doses of pure wormwood vapour, and another to alcohol vapours.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The guinea pig exposed to wormwood vapour experienced convulsive seizures, while the animal exposed to alcohol did not.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Magnan would later blame the naturally occurring (in wormwood) chemical thujone for these effects.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Thujone, once widely believed to be an active chemical in absinthe, is a GABA antagonist, and while it can produce muscle spasms in large doses, there is no direct evidence to suggest it causes hallucinations.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Past reports estimated thujone concentrations in absinthe as being up to 260 mg/kg.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] As such, most traditionally crafted absinthes, both vintage and modern, fall within the current EU standards.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Tests conducted on mice to study toxicity showed an oral LD50 of about 45 mg thujone per kg of body weight, which represents far more absinthe than could be realistically consumed.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The high percentage of alcohol in absinthe would result in mortality long before thujone could become a factor.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] In documented cases of acute thujone poisoning as a result of oral ingestion, the source of thujone was not commercial absinthe, but rather non-absinthe-related sources, such as common essential oils (which may contain as much as 50% thujone).
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] One study published in the *Journal of Studies on Alcohol* concluded that high doses (0.28 mg/kg) of thujone in alcohol had negative effects on attention performance in a clinical setting.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] It delayed reaction time, and caused subjects to concentrate their attention on the central field of vision.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Low doses (0.028 mg/kg) did not produce an effect noticeably different from the plain alcohol control.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] While the effects of the high dose samples were statistically significant in a double blind test, the test subjects themselves were unable to reliably identify which samples contained thujone.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] For the average 65 kg (143 lb) man, the high dose samples in the study would equate to 18.2 mg of thujone.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The EU limit of 35 mg/L of thujone in absinthe means that given the highest permitted thujone content, that individual would need to consume approximately 0.5 litres of high-proof (e.g.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] 50%+ ABV) spirit before the thujone could be metabolized to display effects detectable in a clinical setting, which would result in a potentially lethal BAC of >0.4%.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Most countries (except Switzerland) at present do not possess a legal definition of absinthe (unlike Scotch whisky or cognac).
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Accordingly, producers are free to label a product "absinthe" or "absinth", whether or not it bears any resemblance to the traditional spirit.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Absinthe is readily available in many bottle shops.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Bitters may contain a maximum 35 mg/kg thujone, while other alcoholic beverages can contain a maximum 10 mg/kg.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The domestic production and sale of absinthe is regulated by state licensing laws.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] These controls have now been repealed, and permission is no longer required.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Absinthe was prohibited in Brazil until 1999 and was brought by entrepreneur Lalo Zanini and legalised in the same year.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Presently, absinthe sold in Brazil must abide by the national law that restricts all spirits to a maximum of 54% ABV.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] While this regulation is enforced throughout channels of legal distribution, it may be possible to find absinthe containing alcohol in excess of the legal limit in some restaurants or food fairs.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] In Canada, liquor laws concerning the production, distribution, and sale of spirits are written and enforced by individual provincial government monopolies.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Each product is subject to the approval of a respective individual provincial liquor board before it can be sold in that province.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Importation is a federal matter and is enforced by the Canada Border Services Agency.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The importation of a nominal amount of liquor by individuals for personal use is permitted, provided that conditions for the individual's duration of stay outside the country are satisfied.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] In 2007, Canada's first genuine absinthe (Taboo Absinthe) was created by Okanagan Spirits Craft Distillery in British Columbia.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The European Union permits a maximum thujone level of 35 mg/kg in alcoholic beverages where *Artemisia* species is a listed ingredient, and 10 mg/kg in other alcoholic beverages.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Member countries regulate absinthe production within this framework.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The sale of absinthe is permitted in all EU countries unless they further regulate it.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The sale and production of absinthe was prohibited in Finland from 1919 to 1932; no current prohibitions exist.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The government-owned chain of liquor stores (Alko) is the only outlet that may sell alcoholic beverages containing over 8% ABV, although national law bans the sale of alcoholic beverages containing over 80% ABV.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Édouard Manet's first major painting *The Absinthe Drinker* was controversial, and was rejected by the Paris Salon in 1859.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] French producers circumvented this regulatory obstacle by labelling absinthe as *spiritueux à base de plantes d'absinthe* ('wormwood-based spirits'), with many either reducing or omitting fennel and hyssop altogether from their products.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] A legal challenge to the scientific basis of this decree resulted in its repeal (2009), which opened the door for the official French re-legalisation of absinthe for the first time since 1915.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The French Senate voted to repeal the prohibition in mid-April 2011.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] A ban on absinthe was enacted in Germany on 27 March 1923.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] In addition to banning the production of commercial trade in absinthe, the law went so far as to prohibit the distribution of printed matter that provided details of its production.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The original ban was lifted in 1981, but the use of *Artemisia absinthium* as a flavouring agent remained prohibited.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] On 27 September 1991, Germany adopted the European Community's standards of 1988, which effectively re-legalised absinthe.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The Fascist regime in 1926 banned the production, import, transport, and sale of any liquor named *Assenzio*.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The ban was reinforced in 1931 with harsher penalties for transgressors and remained in force until 1992 when the Italian government amended its laws to comply with the EU directive 88/388/EEC.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Although absinthe is not prohibited at the national level, some local authorities have banned it.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The ban came in August 2008 after several issues of misuse drew public and police attention.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] One incident resulted in breathing difficulties and hospitalising of a 17-year-old for alcohol poisoning.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The particular brand of absinthe that caused these effects was bottled at 89% ABV.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The sale and production of absinthe has never been prohibited in Sweden or Norway.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] However, the only outlet that may sell alcoholic beverages containing more than 3.5% ABV in Sweden and 4.75% ABV in Norway is the government-owned chain of liquor stores known as Systembolaget in Sweden and Vinmonopolet in Norway.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Systembolaget and Vinmonopolet did not import or sell absinthe for many years after the ban in France; however, today several absinthes are available for purchase in Systembolaget stores, including Swedish made distilled absinthe.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] In Norway, on the other hand, one is less likely to find many absinthes since Norwegian alcohol law prohibits the sale and importation of alcoholic beverages above 60% ABV, which eliminates most absinthes.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] In Switzerland, the sale and production of absinthe was prohibited from 1910 to 1 March 2005.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] This was based on a vote in 1908, inspired by the Jean Lanfray incident.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] To be legally made or sold in Switzerland, absinthe must be distilled, must not contain certain additives, and must be either naturally coloured or left uncoloured.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] In 2014, the Federal Administrative Court of Switzerland invalidated a governmental decision of 2010 which allowed only absinthe made in the Val-de-Travers region to be labelled as absinthe in Switzerland.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The court found that absinthe was a label for a product and was not tied to a geographic origin.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Absinthe was never legally prohibited in the UK, but was not imported for a 70-year period.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] In 2007, the Alcohol and Tobacco Tax and Trade Bureau (TTB) effectively lifted the long-standing absinthe ban, and it has since approved many brands for sale in the US market.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] This was made possible partly through the TTB's clarification of the Food and Drug Administration's (FDA) thujone content regulations, which specify that finished food and beverages that contain *Artemisia* species must be thujone-free.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] In this context, the TTB considers a product thujone-free if the thujone content is less than 10 ppm (equal to 10 mg/kg).
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] This is verified through the use of gas chromatography–mass spectrometry.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The brands Kübler and Lucid and their lawyers did most of the work to get absinthe legalized in the U.S., over the 2004–2007 time period.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] In the U.S., 5 March sometimes is referred to as "National Absinthe Day", as it was the day the 95-year ban on absinthe was finally lifted.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Absinthe imported in violation of these regulations is subject to seizure at the discretion of U.S.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Numerous artists and writers living in France in the late 19th and early 20th centuries were noted absinthe drinkers and featured absinthe in their work.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Some of these included Édouard Manet, Guy de Maupassant, Paul Verlaine, Amedeo Modigliani, Edgar Degas, Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec, Vincent van Gogh, Oscar Wilde, Arthur Rimbaud, and Émile Zola.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Many other renowned artists and writers similarly drew from this cultural well, including Aleister Crowley, Ernest Hemingway, Pablo Picasso, August Strindberg, and Erik Satie.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] The aura of illicitness and mystery surrounding absinthe has played into literature, movies, music, and television, where it is often portrayed as a mysterious, addictive, and mind-altering drink.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Marie Corelli's *Wormwood: A Drama of Paris* (1890) was a popular novel about a Frenchman driven to murder and ruin after being introduced to absinthe.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Intended as a morality tale on the dangers of the drink, it was speculated to have contributed to subsequent bans of absinthe in Europe and the United States.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] Some of the earliest film references include *The Hasher's Delirium* (1910) by Émile Cohl, an early pioneer in the art of animation, as well as two different silent films, each titled *Absinthe*, from 1913 and 1914 respectively.
[src:applejack-drink/absinthe] More recently, it served as the title of a 2018 song by the indie group I Don't Know How But They Found Me.
[src:applejack-drink/acerum] In the 1970s, distillers began to produce alcohol from maple syrup.
[src:applejack-drink/acerum] Although some distilled alcohol tests were then carried out in university laboratories, it was not until the 1990s that certain maple syrup producers began to produce a wine based on this sweet resource, which was initially called Acer.
[src:applejack-drink/acerum] One of the first producers of Acerum was The Domaine Acer, based in Témiscouata, Quebec.
[src:applejack-drink/acerum] When Vallier Robert took the reins of his family maple business in 1990, he quickly saw the potential to make alcohol.
[src:applejack-drink/acerum] In 1996, the maple farmer was granted the first licence to produce artisanal maple-based alcoholic beverages.
[src:applejack-drink/acerum] He began creating several varieties of maple sap wine, including dry, sparkling and dessert wines.
[src:applejack-drink/acerum] During the same period, some distilleries began to market maple eau-de-vie, but it was not until December 2017 that the name Acerum appeared for the first time for a maple eau-de-vie.
[src:applejack-drink/acerum] As defined by the specifications of the UDSÉ, Acerum must be entirely manufactured in the province of Quebec, in Canada, with maple syrup, maple concentrate, or maple sap from Quebec maples.
[src:applejack-drink/adams-pearmain] '**Adams Pearmain**', also called '**Adam's Parmane**', is a cultivar of apple.
[src:applejack-drink/adams-pearmain] It was introduced to the Horticultural Society of London in 1826 by Robert Adams, under the name '**Norfolk Pippin**'.
[src:applejack-drink/adams-pearmain] The fruit is large, varying from two and a half inches to three inches high, and about the same in breadth at the widest part.
[src:applejack-drink/adams-pearmain] It is pearmain-shaped, very even, and regularly formed.
[src:applejack-drink/adams-pearmain] The skin is pale yellow tinged with green, and covered with delicate russet on the shaded side; but deep yellow tinged with red, and delicately streaked with livelier red on the side facing the sun.
[src:applejack-drink/adams-pearmain] The flesh is reddish, crisp, juicy, rich, and sugary, with an agreeable and pleasantly perfumed flavor.
[src:applejack-drink/adams-pearmain] This Cultivar is a sibling of Reinette de Hollande, a hybrid between Reinette Franche’ and ‘Reinette des Carmes.
[src:applejack-drink/advocaat] Two theories have been put out on the origins of "advocaat".
[src:applejack-drink/advocaat] According to several makers, such as Verpoorten and Bols, and the *Oxford Companion to Sugar and Sweets*, its origins can be traced back to "abacate", an alcoholic beverage of the indigenous people in Brazil, which was made with avocado.
[src:applejack-drink/advocaat] Dutch colonials of northern Brazil introduced this beverage to Europe as "advocat/advocaat".
[src:applejack-drink/advocaat] As avocados could not grow in northern Europe, they were replaced with egg yolk, thought to have a similar taste and consistency, and the name derived from the avocado stuck, although the drink no longer contains any.
[src:applejack-drink/advocaat] Cooymans started a distillery in downtown 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:applejack-drink/advocaat] There he developed the egg drink "advocaat".
[src:applejack-drink/advocaat] In 1876, the Antwerp distiller Eugen Verpoorten established a distillery in Heinsberg near Aachen, Germany, which made an egg liqueur (*Eierlikör* in German) using eggs, sugar, distilled alcohol, and other ingredients.
[src:applejack-drink/advocaat] Jars and wide mouth bottles of thick advocaat are sold mainly in the Netherlands and Belgium, though may be available in Germany, Austria, and South Africa.
[src:applejack-drink/advocaat] Further exports are of a more liquid version.
[src:applejack-drink/advocaat] In particular the original thick variety, i.e., without albumen, is used as a waffle, pancake or poffertjes topping, as an ingredient in ice cream, custards, pastries and similar desserts, or as an apéritif or digestif.
[src:applejack-drink/advocaat] The latter, possibly topped with whipped cream and then occasionally sprinkled with a touch of cocoa powder, is served in a very tiny bowl or small glass from which it is eaten by use of a teaspoon.
[src:applejack-drink/advocaat] In Belgian restaurants and taverns, it may be a complementary accompaniment to a coffee.
[src:applejack-drink/advocaat] In the export variety both parts of the eggs are used.
[src:applejack-drink/advocaat] A popular cocktail using advocaat is the Snowball: a mixture of advocaat, sparkling lemonade and sometimes (although this is not required) lime juice that is often consumed at Christmas time.
[src:applejack-drink/advocaat] Another is the Fluffy duck, made with rum.
[src:applejack-drink/advocaat] Another advocaat-based beverage is the Bombardino, a drink commonly found in Italian ski resorts, particularly the Italian Alps, made by mixing advocaat, brandy, and whipped cream.
[src:applejack-drink/advocaat] The Polish equivalent, *ajerkoniak* (German: *eier* 'eggs' and French: *cognac*), is based on vodka instead of brandy, despite what the name may suggest.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] Many plants in this genus may be considered perennial, because they require several to many years to mature and flower.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] However, most *Agave* species are more accurately described as monocarpic rosettes or multiannuals, since each individual rosette flowers only once and then dies; a small number of *Agave* species are polycarpic.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] Along with plants from the closely related genera *Yucca*, *Hesperoyucca*, and *Hesperaloe,* various *Agave* species are popular ornamental plants in hot, dry climates, as they require very little supplemental water to survive.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] Some *Agave* species are known by the common name "century plant".
[src:applejack-drink/agave] In other regions, it goes by different names.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] In the Chinese, Japanese, and Korean languages, it is referred to as the compound word *dragon tongue orchid* (simplified Chinese: 龙舌兰; traditional Chinese: 龍舌蘭; pinyin: *lóngshélán*; Japanese: 竜舌蘭, romanized: *ryūzetsuran*; Korean: 용설란; Hanja: 龍舌蘭; RR: *yongseollan*).
[src:applejack-drink/agave] In Malta, it is referred to as *Sabbara*; In Maltese, Agave americana is referred to as "Sabbara tal-Amerika", and Agave sisalana is referred to as "Sabbara ta' Sisal".
[src:applejack-drink/agave] The succulent leaves of most *Agave* species have sharp marginal teeth, an extremely sharp terminal spine, and are very fibrous inside.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] The stout stem is usually extremely short, which may make the plant appear as though it is stemless.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] Agaves can be confused with cacti, aloes, or stonecrops, but although these plants all share similar morphological adaptations to arid environments (e.g. succulence), each group belongs to a different plant family and probably experienced convergent evolution.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] Further, cactus (Cactaceae) and stonecrop (Crassulaceae) lineages are eudicots, while aloes (Asphodelaceae) and agaves (Asparagaceae) are monocots.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] The agave root system, consisting of a network of shallow rhizomes, allows the agave to efficiently capture moisture from rain, condensation, and dew.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] In addition to growing from seeds, most agaves produce 'pups' – young plants from runners.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] *Agave vilmoriniana* (the octopus agave) produces hundreds of pups on its bloom stalk.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] Agave leaves store the plant's water and are crucial to its continued existence.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] The coated leaf surface prevents evaporation.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] The leaves also have sharp, spiked edges.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] The spikes discourage predators from eating the plant or using it as a source of water and are so tough that ancient peoples used them for sewing needles.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] Some agaves bloom at a height up to 9 m (30 ft) so that they are far out of reach to animals that might attack them.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] Smaller species, such as *Agave lechuguilla*, have smaller bloom stalks.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] The genus name *Agave* come from the Ancient Greek αγαυή *agauê* from ἀγαυός *agauós* meaning "illustrious, noble" having to do with very tall flower spikes found on its many species.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] The genus *Agave* was erected by Carl Linnaeus in 1753, initially with four species.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] The first listed was *Agave americana*, now the type species.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] In the Cronquist system and others, *Agave* was placed in the family Liliaceae, but phylogenetic analyses of DNA sequences later showed it did not belong there.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] In the APG II system, *Agave* was placed in the segregated family Agavaceae.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] When this system was superseded by the APG III system in 2009, the Agavaceae were subsumed into the expanded family Asparagaceae, and *Agave* was treated as one of 18 genera in the subfamily Agavoideae, a position retained in the APG IV system of 2016.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] However, Agavaceae had regained its taxonomic status as an independent family by 2020.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] Agaves and close relatives have long presented significant taxonomic difficulty.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] These difficulties could be due to the relatively young evolutionary age of the group (major diversification events of the group most likely occurred 8–10 million years ago), ease of hybridization between species (and even genera), incomplete lineage sorting, and long generation times.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] Within a species, morphological variations can be considerable, especially in cultivation; many named species may be variants of original wild-type species that horticulturalists bred to appear unique in cultivation.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] With the advent of DNA sequencing, new karyologic and evolutionary phylogenetic studies showed that the genera *Manfreda*, *Polianthes* and *Prochnyanthes* were genetically nested within the traditional circumscription of *Agave*, rendering the genus paraphyletic.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] Early in the 21st century, these new phylogenetic results led to a reclassification of to include *Manfreda*, *Polianthes* and *Prochnyanthes* together as *Agave* subgenus *Manfreda*.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] There was reaction against the changes from those who noted that the large morphological differences between the genera in this new *Agave* s.l. making them "counter-intuitive from a horticultural point of view".
[src:applejack-drink/agave] *Manfreda* morphologically differs from the classic *Agave* description in being herbaceous and bulbous, while *Polianthes* are deciduous with narrow leaves and no spines.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] Mexican taxonomists have continued to adhere to the traditional classifications and have published new species of *Polianthes*.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] Thus, based on a wider consideration of previously established genetic, morphological, and estimated genetic divergence times, Vázquez-García et al. proposed a narrower circumscription of *Agave* by creating three new genera: *Echinoagave*, *Paleoagave* and *Paraagave*.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] These new genera have gained some acceptance, and pave the way for a reconsideration of *Manfreda*, *Polianthes* and *Prochnyanthes*.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] Some commonly grown species include *Agave americana*, *A. angustifolia*, *A. attenuata*, *A. murpheyi*, *A. palmeri*, *A. parryi*, *A. parviflora*, *A. tequilana*, *A. victoriae-reginae*, and *A. vilmoriniana*.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] One of the most familiar species is *A. americana*, a native of tropical America.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] Common names include century plant, *maguey* (in Mexico), or American aloe (though not related to the genus *Aloe*).
[src:applejack-drink/agave] The name "century plant" refers to the long time the plant takes to flower.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] The number of years before flowering occurs depends on the vigor of the individual plant, the richness of the soil, and the climate; during these years, the plant is storing in its fleshy leaves the nourishment required for the effort of flowering.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] Some species contain components in their juice which can cause dermatitis for some people.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] The ethnobotany of the agave was described by William H.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] The four major edible parts of the agave are the flowers, the leaves, the stalks or basal rosettes, and the sap (in Spanish: *aguamiel*, meaning "honey water").
[src:applejack-drink/agave] The sap of some species can also be used as soap.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] Each agave plant produces several pounds of edible flowers during its final season.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] The stalks, which are ready during the summer, before the blossom, weigh several pounds each.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] Roasted, they are sweet and can be chewed to extract the sap or *aguamiel*, like sugarcane.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] When dried out, the stalks can be used to make didgeridoos.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] The leaves may be collected in winter and spring, when the plants are rich in sap, for eating.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] The leaves of several species also yield fiber, for instance, *A. sisalana*, the sisal hemp, and *A. decipiens*, the false sisal hemp.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] *A. americana* is the source of pita fiber, and is used as a fiber plant in Mexico, the West Indies, and southern Europe.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] The agave, especially *A. murpheyi*, was a major food source for the prehistoric indigenous people of the Southwestern United States.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] The Hohokam of southern Arizona cultivated large areas of agave.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] The Navajo similarly found many uses for the agave plant.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] A beverage is squeezed from the baked fibers, and the heads can be baked or boiled, pounded into flat sheets, sun dried, and stored for future use.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] The baked, dried heads are also boiled and made into an edible paste, eaten whole, or made into soup.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] The leaves are eaten boiled, and the young, tender flowering stalks and shoots are roasted and eaten as well.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] The fibers are used to make rope, the leaves are used to line baking pits, and the sharp-pointed leaf tips are used to make basketry awls.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] During the development of the inflorescence, sap rushes to the base of the young flower stalk.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] Agave syrup (commonly called agave nectar), a sweetener derived from the sap, is used as an alternative to sugar in cooking, and can be added to breakfast cereals as a binding agent.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] Extracts from agave leaves are under preliminary research for their potential use as food additives.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] The sap of *A. americana* and other species is used in Mexico and Mesoamerica to produce pulque, an alcoholic beverage.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] The flower shoot is cut out and the sap collected and subsequently fermented.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] By distillation, a spirit called mezcal is prepared; one of the best-known forms of mezcal is tequila.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] *azul* is used in the production of tequila.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] *A. angustifolia* is widely used in the production of mezcal and pulque, though at least 10 other *Agave* species are also known to be used for this.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] Agave can be used as the raw material for industrial production of fructans as a prebiotic dietary fiber.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] Agave contains fructooligosaccharides, which are naturally occurring oligosaccharides that support safely subjecting peanut-allergic people to allergen immunotherapy.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] Resulting from its natural habitat in stressful environments, agave is under preliminary research for its potential use in germplasm conservation and in biotechnology to better anticipate the economic effects of global climate change.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] It may also have use as a bioethanol or bioenergy feedstock.
[src:applejack-drink/agave] Agave plantations have potential applications on marginal lands unsuitable for grain crops.
[src:applejack-drink/applejack-drink] Very popular in the early- to mid-colonial era, the drink's prevalence declined in the 17th- and 18th-centuries amid competition from other alcoholic spirits as they became easier to manufacture.
[src:applejack-drink/applejack-drink] Applejack experienced a revival during the Prohibition era, primarily due to the drink's ease-of-manufacture, but again declined in prevalence after the repeal of Prohibition.
[src:applejack-drink/applejack-drink] It experienced another resurgence in popularity in the mid-2010s and early-2020s.
[src:applejack-drink/applejack-drink] Applejack is generally considered to be a type of brandy and is, in the United States, legally classified as such.
[src:applejack-drink/applejack-drink] Applejack is used in several cocktails, including the Jack Rose.
[src:applejack-drink/applejack-drink] Applejack was first produced in colonial New Jersey in 1698 by William Laird, a Scots American who settled in Monmouth County.
[src:applejack-drink/applejack-drink] The drink was once known as **Jersey Lightning**.
[src:applejack-drink/applejack-drink] Laird's great-grandson, Robert Laird, who served in the Continental Army, incorporated Laird's Distillery in 1780, after previously operating a tavern.
[src:applejack-drink/applejack-drink] The oldest licensed applejack distillery in the United States, Laird & Company of Scobeyville, New Jersey, was until the 2000s the country's only remaining producer of applejack, and continues to dominate applejack production.
[src:applejack-drink/applejack-drink] Once popular in early America, applejack declined in popularity due to the rise of other spirits that were easier to manufacture on a commercial basis, including rum and whiskey (especially bourbon) in the 19th century and gin, vodka, and tequila in the 20th century.
[src:applejack-drink/applejack-drink] In 1920, with the beginning of the Prohibition era, Laird's ended the production of liquor and began producing apple juice.
[src:applejack-drink/applejack-drink] In 1931, John Evans Laird received permission to produce apple brandy for "medicinal purposes" and stockpiled its product until the repeal of Prohibition in 1933.
[src:applejack-drink/applejack-drink] Applejack has been associated with four presidents of the United States: after the American Revolution, George Washington requested from Robert Laird his family's recipe for applejack; Abraham Lincoln served it during a brief stint as a tavern keeper in Springfield, Illinois; Franklin D.
[src:applejack-drink/applejack-drink] Roosevelt included applejack in the Manhattans he regularly consumed; and Lyndon B.
[src:applejack-drink/applejack-drink] Johnson gave a case of applejack to Soviet leader Alexei Kosygin in the 1967 Glassboro Summit Conference.
[src:applejack-drink/applejack-drink] In the 2010s, a number of smaller craft distilleries began to produce applejack in places such as New Hampshire, Pennsylvania's Lehigh Valley, New York's Hudson Valley, Holland, Michigan, and in Toronto.
[src:applejack-drink/applejack-drink] The name *applejack* derives from the traditional method of producing the drink, *jacking*, which is the process of freezing fermented cider and then removing the ice, increasing the alcohol content.
[src:applejack-drink/applejack-drink] Cider produced after the fall harvest was left outside during the winter.
[src:applejack-drink/applejack-drink] Periodically the frozen chunks of ice that had formed were removed, thus concentrating the unfrozen alcohol in the remaining liquid.
[src:applejack-drink/applejack-drink] An alternative method involved placing a cask of hard cider in snow, allowing ice to form on the inside of the cask as the contents began to freeze, and then tapping the cask and pouring off the still-liquid portion of the contents.
[src:applejack-drink/applejack-drink] Starting with the fermented juice, with an alcohol content of less than ten percent, the concentrated result can contain 25–40% alcohol.
[src:applejack-drink/applejack-drink] Because freeze distillation is a low-infrastructure method of production compared to evaporative distillation, and does not require the burning of firewood to create heat, hard cider and applejack were historically easier to produce, though more expensive than grain alcohol.
[src:applejack-drink/applejack-drink] The disadvantage of freeze distillation, also called fractional crystallization, is that the substances remaining after the removal of the water include not only ethanol, but also harmful methanol, esters, aldehydes, and fusel alcohols.
[src:applejack-drink/applejack-drink] In modern times, reducing methanol with the absorption of a molecular sieve is a practical method for production.
[src:applejack-drink/applejack-drink] When commercial production began, applejack was also starting to be produced through evaporative distillation.
[src:applejack-drink/applejack-drink] Modern commercially produced applejack is often no longer produced by jacking but rather by blending apple brandy and neutral grain spirits.
[src:applejack-drink/applejack-drink] Applejack is somewhat similar to calvados, an apple brandy from Normandy, France, to which it is often compared.
[src:applejack-drink/applejack-drink] However, calvados is made from cider apples, while applejack is made from apples such as Winesap.
